🧠 2) DSA — SLIDING WINDOW (REAL-TIME ENGINE)
🔥 Core Idea

Sliding window = efficient continuous computation

🧠 Deep Understanding
Instead of:
Recompute every window → O(n*k)
Use:
Update window → O(n)
🔥 Example
def max_sum(arr, k):
    window_sum = sum(arr[:k])
    max_sum = window_sum

    for i in range(k, len(arr)):
        window_sum += arr[i] - arr[i-k]
        max_sum = max(max_sum, window_sum)

    return max_sum
⚙️ Real-Time Usage
✔ Trading Systems
moving average price
rolling profit
✔ Fraud Detection
transactions in last 10 mins
✔ Monitoring Systems
error rate in last 5 mins
🧠 Advanced Concepts
✔ Fixed vs Variable Window
Type	Use
Fixed	average
Variable	longest substring
✔ Streaming Data

👉 window moves with incoming data

🎯 SCENARIO QUESTIONS
❓ Q1: Data is streaming continuously

💬 Strong Answer:

“Sliding window is ideal for streaming data as it allows incremental updates without recomputing values, making it efficient for real-time systems.”

❓ Q2: Window size is very large

💬 Strong Answer:

“I would optimize memory usage by maintaining only necessary state and possibly using approximate algorithms if exact computation is too expensive.”

❓ Q3: Need both historical and real-time data

💬 Strong Answer:

“I would combine sliding window for real-time processing with batch processing or prefix sums for historical data.”

🧠 GS-Level Answer

👉 “When do you use sliding window?”

“Sliding window is used for problems involving continuous subarrays or streams of data. It allows efficient computation by maintaining a running window instead of recalculating values repeatedly, reducing time complexity to O(n).”

